name: fastapi-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for FastAPI applications and documentation
globs: **/*.py
---

- Use Pydantic BaseModel for request and response validation.
- Document each endpoint with clear descriptions and examples.
- Utilize FastAPI's automatic OpenAPI documentation features.
- Implement proper status codes for responses.
- Use dependency injection for shared logic and database connections.

---
name: pydantic-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for using Pydantic models in FastAPI
globs: **/*.py
---

- Define models using BaseModel for data validation and serialization.
- Use field types and constraints to enforce data integrity.
- Implement custom validators for complex validation logic.
- Leverage model inheritance for shared attributes.
- Document model fields with descriptions for better API documentation.

---
name: sqlalchemy-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for SQLAlchemy ORM usage in FastAPI
globs: **/*.py
---

- Use declarative base for model definitions.
- Implement relationships using foreign keys and back_populates.
- Use session management to handle database connections efficiently.
- Avoid using raw SQL queries; prefer ORM methods for safety.
- Implement migrations using Alembic for database schema changes.

---
name: uvicorn-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for running FastAPI applications with Uvicorn
globs: **/*.py
---

- Use `--host` and `--port` flags to specify server settings.
- Enable `--reload` during development for automatic code reloading.
- Use `--workers` to run multiple instances for better performance.
- Configure logging to monitor application behavior.
- Set up proper timeout settings to handle long-running requests.

---
name: pytest-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for testing FastAPI applications with Pytest
globs: **/*.py
---

- Use fixtures to set up test data and application context.
- Write tests for each endpoint to ensure functionality.
- Use `TestClient` from FastAPI for making requests in tests.
- Implement coverage checks to ensure all code paths are tested.
- Organize tests in a dedicated directory for clarity.